{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_alastor_ver02/data/sn78003992/00340580928/1945081001/0282.xml":{"full_text":"uo XuttMS,.pfllCfl\nSo Labor\nMay Know\n*\u2019vl i i\nSome folks well worth knowing\nare coitfing yoyr way in the next few\nweeks*\nThey may or may not be the kind\nof people you\u2019d want for company on\nA fishing trip or for a game of poker.\nBut whether you find them congenial\nOf not, they're still worth knowing,\nfor very practical reasons.\nIt so happens these folks have a lot\nto say about yotir job, your earnings,\nwhat\u2019s going to happen to you if you\n16 s* your job, what you and your\nfamily are going to eat and wear, how\nyou're going to be housed, and what\nsort of opportunity'your children will\nhave in life.\nThi folks who are coming your way*\nire your representatives in Congress,\nnow preparing to return home for the\nsummer recess.\nIf you doubt they have as much to\nsay about your personal affairs as\nwe\u2019ve indicated, just consider some of\nthe bills they\u2019ve been arguing about\nor cold-shouldering in Congress.\nLook through the cellophane of\nlong-winded speeches, personal and\nparty politics, and the gobbled\u2019gook\nof legislative terminology\u2014and you\nwill see your job, your wages, your\nsavings and your future wrapped up\nin the packages they handle, labeled\nHR No. this and S, No. that,\nYou need sewage increase, and your\nunion could probably get you a good\node if its hands were freed. But un\nder\" the 'Little Steel formula, it can\nqnly go so far and no further.\n'The administration will be influ\nenced in its decision on wages by a\npetition now circulating in Congress\nto break through the Little Steel wage\nfreeze.\n\u25a0r It\u2019s worth getting acquainted with\nyoiir Congressman, just to find out if\nlie has signed this petition, if for noth\ning, else.\nIf you are .one of the ten million\nAmericans subsisting. on substandard\nwages of less than 65 cents an hour,\nyour interest is obvious in the bill to'\ntike the minimum wage under the\nFair Labor Standards Act to 65 cents\nan, hour.\nEven if you aren\u2019t, you can never\nbe sure that unemployment will not,\nforce you one day to take a job,at\nsubstaiidaird -wafee*i-mtd-4a^awy -ease,\nyour higher wage rates will \"never be\nsecure so long as millions of your\nfellows arc paid less than a living\nWage.\nYou\u2019ll surely want to know what\nyour representatives in Congress are\ngoing to do about this bill.\n\nWhat\u2019s going to happen to you and\nyour family, if you get laid off\nthrough the cutbacks that are.closing\nmore and more plants?\nAs things stand, you won\u2019t get\nenough to live/ on under the various\nstate unemployment compensation\nlaws, and youJll get this little for very\nfew weeks.\nBut there\u2019s a bill before Congress,\nintroduced by Senator Kilgore and\nSeveral other Senators, to raise emer\ngency unemployment benefits to $25\nto 26 weeks; to cover federal, mari\ntime and other workers who now get\nno protection Whatever; to increase\nveterans\u2019 benefits; and to pay travel\ncosts to new jobs.\n\u2018What are your representatives in\nCongress going to do about this'bill,\nand are they going to act on it in\ntime?\na\n.i' S'- '.V t 4 ,;v\nAre you goingj to have a fair shot\nat new jobs and an equal chance for\npromotion, or are you going to be\ndiscriminated against because of your\ncolor, race, religion or national\noHgin?\nWhen your Congress goes home,\nyou\u2019ll want to know what they have\ndone to save the present Fair Em\nployment Practice Committee and\nwhat they\u2019re going to do about a\npermanent FEPC.\nAnd you\u2019ll certainly want to know\nif they\u2019re going to push through the\nWagner-Murray Dingell bill to pro\nvide you with some decent security\nagainst the,hazards of age, illness, un\nemployment, etc.; and what\u2019s cooking\non the MurrSy-Patman Full Employ\nment bill End other plans to provide\njobs for all.\nAll this is your personal business,\nas well as the people\u2019s business. It\nalso happens to be the legislative pro\ngram adopted by the CIO Executive\nBoard and Political Action Commit\ntee. The coming recess will give you\na good chance to ask your representa\nlives in Congress what they propose\nto do about it. f\n.*'5\n;S0:\nl\n\n\n,.vt- s, I t\nf;\nOFFICIAL PUBLICATION OP ORGANIZED LABOR IN-AKRON AND VICINITY\nft\n1\n4 V i\nCooperates With A. F. of L. and CIO Labor Unions of Summit, Medina, Portage* Wayne add Surrounding Counties Member of International Labor Press of America.\n\"-'Ivr.\nFORAII\nALL FOR\nONE\nVol. 2$\u2014 No. 31\nAKRON, OHIO,FRIDAY, AUGUST 10, 1945\n$2.00 PER YEAR\nCIO Program Means\nJobs And Security,\nMurray Asserts\nBy PHILIP MURRAY\nPresident Congress of Industrial Organizations r\nAre wages abnormally high in the United States? No. The over\nwhelming majority of, the workers in this country today are not\nmaking high wages. Most of them, according to the government\u2019s\nown figures, are having difficulty'*\nmaking ends meet even with over\ntime work and oth'er temporary means\nof increasing their income through in\ncreased labor.\nAs we study the statistics, as* we re\nlate them to the cost of living, and as\nwe compare them to profits, we find a\nvastly different picture from Ihe opti\nmistic one so frequently painted in\nthe newspapers and even in official\npronouncements.\nThe basic wage structure, used in\nthis country during wartime is the\nLittle Steel formula. Under this,\nWEEKLY LABOR\nRADIO SHOWS\nUnited* R ubber Workers of\nAmerica will broadcast a program\neach Wednesday evening at 6:45\nover Radio- Station WHKK, Ak\nron, 640 on your dials, for the en\ntertainment' and education of all\n\u2022fisteners ie the-greater Akron area: s\nThe program will be transcribed\nand repeated each Wednesday\nnight at 10:45 o\u2019clock. It' is a\nworth-while program! Listen to it\neach Wednesday.\n(The \u201cXFL Radio Show\u201d is a reg\nlar Saturday night feature of Radio\nStation WAKR. It comes on the\nair at 6:45 and lasts until 7 o\u2019clock.\nIt is a' very good program. Listen to\nit regularly.\nformula, increases in the basic wage\nwere held to 15 per cent of the\namount-earned in 1941.\nThe theory on which this rigid Lit\n(Continucd on Page\nh\nGoodrich Local\nIs Victor In\nPact Case\n^Members of Goodrich Local No. S.\nUnited Rubber Workers of America,\nwere awarded maintenance of mem\nbership and the check-off of union\ndues in' an opinion rendered by the\nRegional 'War Labor Board in Cleve\nland. Tlie company was instructed\nto include the provisions in the new\ncontract between company and the lo\ncal signed a week ago.\nAlthough the maintenance of mem\nbership and check-off had been a part\noi the contract between the company\nand the local signed in 1943, the com\npany objected to including the pro\nvisions in the new contract for alleged\nunauthorized work stoppages by emr\npidyCi during the .past two years. It\nwas willing to agree to the mainte\nnance of membership, however, if a\nfifteen-day escape clause were in\nserted. The NLRB, opinion denied\nthe company\u2019s request.\nIn the lengthy opinion made by the\nboard, unauthorized work stoppages\nwere condemned. The concession to\nthe local in continuing the clauses in\nthe contract was made conditional on\nno further work stoppages at the\nplant.\nIn a resolution adopted by members\nof Goodrich Local last Sunday, it was\nvoted to appeal the decision of Harry\nC. Markle, District War Manpower\n(Continued on Page Four)\nLABOR LEADERS APPLAUD EXPOSE CONTAINED IN SERIES OF ARTICLE? WRITTEN BY CORRESPONDENT EUGENE SEGAL\nEditor\u2019s Note: The following is a resume of six articles\nabout the backers, aims and plots of the so-called \u201cNationalist\nParty which appeared in all Scripps-Howard Newspapers\nlast month. William Green, president of the American Feder\nation of Labor, and Philip Murray, president of Congress of\nIndustrial Organizations, loudly endorsed the series of articles\nwritten by Eugene Segal.\n.ip.\u2014\u2014.\nAFL President William Green Says:\n\u201cHie shocking disclosures published by the Scripps\nHoward newspapers with regard to the organization of hate\ncampaigns in America should serve as k powerful reminder\nthat the war against Fascism has not yet been won on the\nhome front.\n.Every decent and intelligent American must realize that\nthose who seek to incite prejudice and promote discrimination\nare the real enemies of our democracy, no matter how flam\nboyantly they wrap themselves in the American flag.\nSignificantly, we find the hate propaganda directed not\nonly against racial and religious groups but also against labor.\nThis is a shrewd and profitable device by which the unprinci-\npled racketeer elements who lurk behind the scenes of the\nhate movements have managed to line their pockets with con\ntributions from wealthy anti-labor individuals.\nAs president of the American Federation of Labor I wish\nto commend the Scripps-Howard newspapers for exposing the\ndangerous plans and activities of the so-called Nationalists\nparty.\u201d\nEN GARDE!\nBy RUTH TAYLOR\n\u201cWhat house is So strong or what state so enduring that it can\nnot be utterly overthrown by animosities and divisions?\u201d So wrote\nCicero nearly two thdusand yea*s ago.\n\u201cA warning against divisive tactics again!** you will say. \u201cBut\ndon\u2019t you know the war is won?\u201d\nOf course it is won, but in the winning we can suffer a bitter\ndefeat. Of what avail is a Pyrrhic victory? The unity which grew\nup overnight when Nve were attacked is showing signs of being too\nquick a construction job. There are cracks across it and the\nbreaches in the walls brought about by group hatreds and prejudices\nhave not been mended.\nListen to people talk today. Notice how quick they are to\nblame their neighbors for all \u00a3hat is troublesome. I>e had three ex\namples of this recently. A labor man, whom I had always counted\non as being as conservative as myself, showed me a flagrant example\nof self-interest on the part of one firm, and said \u201cThis is the attitude\nof industry.\u201d AnotKer man whom I have always respected for his\nfairness, startled me by his generalized denunciation of all labor\nafter an outlaw' strike condemned by labor itself. A third man* a\nliberal of liberals, njade me sick at heart by a virulent diatribe\nagainst minority groups. y\nThese are cracks in the wall. These are signs'of danger. The\ngreatest peril, however, will Come when the siege halts und the men\nare withdrawn from the walls. Then, if we let it happen, disunity\nwill divide us into small, self-seeking groups. Then will the breaches\nwiden until a small fonse can march in and seize the state,\nIt has happened, before. It can happen again. And it will hap\npen to us unless YVef Use care in 'preventing it. We must man the\nramparts in the hour of calm as watchfully as in the heat of battle.\nWe niu&t stand shoulder to shoulder in the reconstruction of the\nw'orld, never slackening in our fight against divisive influences. We\nmust remain on guard to preserve our unity.\nIn the w'ords of that great spokesman of unity, General Smuts\nus go fra|,*f auawlid inas united i\nfellow citizens in a free world.\u201d\nMILLIONS OF AMERICANS\nGET SUB-STANDARD PAY\nMillions of American men and\nwomen workers\u2014and their families\u2014\nare forced today to \"exist on earn\nings insufficient to provide even the\nbarest minimum standard of living\nconsistent with health ^ntf decency.\"\nthe Pepper committee pf the UV S.\nSeriate said this week iq releasing its\nreport on sub-standard wages.\nThe report supports ;rhe need for\nthe bill put in by Senator Pepper (R.,\nFla.) and other Senators raising the\npresent wage hour minimum from *0\ncent9 an hour to 65.\n(This bill\u2019 was reported in the July\n23, CIO NEWS as applying the 65\ncent minimum to a 44,hour work week\nfor the first year, 42 for the second\nand 40 for subsequent years. It now\n(Continued on Page 4)\nRepresentatives Of $6\nDifferent Groups\nAttend Session\nThe six-point national legislative, program of the Congress of\nIndustrial Organizations took a long step forward\u2014at least as far\nas Summit County is concerned\u2014when representatives of 56 differ\nent organizations attended a meeting Sunday afternoon in Goodrich\nlocal\u2019s hall. 708 South Main street.\nMurray Blasts\nAttempts To\nHurt Labor\nCIO President Murray last week\nlabeled the proposed Federal Indus\ntrial Relations Act as a \u201cbald-faced\nattempt to destroy labor unions\u201d and\n\u201ca bill to enslave labor.\u201d. Full text of\nhis remarks follov's:\nThe bill drafted by Donald Rich\nberg and proposed by three senators\nis called \u201cThe Federal Industrial Re\nlations Act.\u201d This is a misnomer.\nThe bill should b^ properly called \u201ca\nbill to enslave labor.\u201d\nFirst, the proposed bill tears the\nheart out of the Wagner Act, the\nMagna Carta of labor. Under ,the\nguise of affording equality of protec\ntioir to .employers.- the' rights'' now\nguaranteed to workers by the Wagner\nAct are -practically eliminated.\nIn addition, full opportunity is af\nforded to employers to interfere and\nhamper efforts of workers to organ\nize and engage in collective bargain\ning, through interminable proceedings\nwhich may be initiated by employers.\nSecond, while employes are author- I\nized to take any unilateral action they\nmay desire, disputes arising therefrom\nare subjected to long drawn out pro\nceedings before one tribunal after\nanother and ending up in compulsory\narbitration. In the meantime, labor\ncan *do nothing *.o protect itself\n(Continued on Page Four)\nIt was one of the largest and best\nmeetings of its kind ever held in: Ak\nron. Twenty-one of the organizations\nrepresented at the meeting are not\nconnected with the CIO.\nThe six-point legislative pVogram\ndiscussed at the meeting provides for\nthe protection of workers in,the post\nwar period. The points are:\n1. Increasing the present mini\nmum wage from 40 to 65 cents per\nhour, with a gradual further in\nAUIC NOTICE!\nThe next regular business meet\ning of Akron Industrial: Union\nCouncil will be held in Goodrich.\nLocal\u2019s hall, 708 South Main street,\non Friday night, August 10th. The\nmeeting will be called to order -at\n7:30 o\u2019clock by President F. B.\nVan Houten. This announcement: k\nthe official notice and the only no-\n-4toe of th\u00bb meeting to be glvbwtd t'.\ndelegates and other persons desir\ning to attend the meeting.\nThe next regular meeting of the\nOrganization Committee will be\nheld in the offices of the Council,\n714 South Main street, on Wednes\nday night, August 22nd. The Exec\nutive Committee of the Council\nwill hold its next regular business\nmeeting in the Council\u2019s offices on\nThursday night, August 23rid\ncrease to 75 cents per hour'during\nthe next two years.\n2. To break the Little Steel Wage\nFormula by authorizing a 20 per\n(Continued on Page 4)\nand the Rev. Harvey Springer, a Denver rabble-rouser often called\n\"The cowboy preacher,\u201d approach religious and youth groups.\nCarl Mote\u2019s rise to power in the \u201cNational Farmer\u2019s Guild\u201d is\ntypical of the intrigues of Nationalists leaders, always alert for op\nportunities to muscle into economic and political organizations. The\n\u201cFarmer\u2019s Guild,\u201d reactionary off-shoot of the Farmer\u2019s Union, in\ncludes a large percentage of former followers of Father Charles E.\n(Continued on Paye Four)\nCIO President Philip Murray Says:\n\u201cI wish to congratulate the Scripps-Howard newspapers\nfor the rgcent series of articles by Eugene Segal on the activi\nties of the Nationalist party and affiliated groups. The reports\nwell reveal the mechanisms of blind prejudice by which these\norganizations spread the. hate which is so fatal to democracy.\nLabor has always been a. target for such pernicious\ngroups. Labor-baiting is one of their most prominent symp\ntoms, as it is of fascism. ,.v'\nIn the period immediately ahead, with the uncertainties\nand hardships of reconversion, many well-meaning people\nmay fall prey, unless forewarned, to the easy opportunity to\nvent grievances offered by the Nationalists and their like.\nThese articles will help every American to realize that in\nfighting these insidious organizations he is helping to protect\nnot only labor unions and minority racial and religious'\ngroups, but himself and his family and the institutions of\ndemocracy.\u201d\nBACK\ni\nUP THE BOYS\nWITH BONDS","height":"27328","width":"21536"}}
